Heavy-tailed Gompertz Models with Stan

Sean Anderson

Lets fit a Gompertz model with heavy-tailed process error to a time series of grey heron counts from England. This is population ID 20579 from the Global Population Dynamics Database.

(Data from Brooks, B., Traill, L. W., Bradshaw, C. J. A. 2006 Minimum viable population sizes and global extinction risk are unrelated. Ecology Letters, 9 (4), 375-382.)

Well start by loading some packages and setting some options:

knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir = "..")
library(rstan)
library(bayesplot)
rstan_options(auto_write = TRUE)
options(mc.cores = parallel::detectCores())
library(ggplot2)
theme_set(theme_light())

Lets read in the data:

d <- read.csv("data/grey-heron.csv")[,2:3]
# d <- read.csv("data/wind-speed.csv")
names(d) <- c("year", "index")
ggplot(d, aes(year, log(index))) +
  geom_point()

You can see the basic model we will work with in the file R/stan/gompertz.stan.

We can fit that model with Stan:

m <- stan("R/stan/gompertz.stan",
  data = list(N = nrow(d), y = log(d$index), nu_rate = 0.01),
  iter = 800)

Lets look at the parameters from our model:

pars <- c("lambda", "b", "sigma_proc", "nu")
print(m, pars = pars)

traceplot(m, pars = pars)

mcmc_hist(as.matrix(m), pars = pars)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# mcmc_areas(as.matrix(m), pars = pars)
# shinystan::launch_shinystan(m)

We can extract the posterior samples with the function rstan::extract(). Part of the Stan code calculated predictions from our model. Alternatively, we could calculate them in R ourselves. We will also calculate residuals from our model.

e <- extract(m)
pred <- data.frame(
  est = apply(e$pred, 2, median),
  l = apply(e$pred, 2, quantile, probs = 0.025),
  h = apply(e$pred, 2, quantile, probs = 0.975),
  year = d$year)
pred$resid <- log(d$index) - pred$est
thresh <- qnorm(0.0001, 0, sd = median(e$sigma_proc))

Lets plot our predictions with the data overlaid:

ggplot(pred, aes(year, est, ymin = l, ymax = h)) +
  geom_ribbon(alpha = 0.4) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point(aes(y = log(d$index)))

And we can look at which residuals exceed some arbitrary threshold:

ggplot(pred, aes(year, resid)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = c(thresh, -thresh), lty = 2)

As a comparison, we could fit the model with normally distributed process error. We can compare the models with the leave-one-out information criterion (LOOIC).

Also notice that the parameter estimates differ.

Lets try fitting our model to a second data set where there arent extremes. This time we will use a data set of population counts for house wrens in the mid 20th century in Illinois, USA. GPDD population ID 28.

(Data reference: Kendeigh, S.C. 1982 Bird populations in east central Illinois: fluctuations, variation and development over a half-century. Illinois Biological Monographs, 52:1-136)

d_hw <- read.csv("data/house-wren.csv")[,2:3]
names(d_hw) <- c("year", "index")
ggplot(d_hw, aes(year, index)) +
  geom_point()

m_hw <- stan("R/stan/gompertz.stan", 
  data = list(N = nrow(d_hw), y = log(d_hw$index), nu_rate = 0.01),
  iter = 800)
print(m_hw, pars = pars)
## Inference for Stan model: gompertz.
## 4 chains, each with iter=800; warmup=400; thin=1; 
## post-warmup draws per chain=400, total post-warmup draws=1600.
## 
##             mean se_mean    sd  2.5%   25%   50%    75%  97.5% n_eff Rhat
## lambda      0.60    0.01  0.36 -0.09  0.36  0.59   0.84   1.32   574 1.01
## b           0.81    0.00  0.11  0.58  0.73  0.81   0.88   1.02   566 1.01
## sigma_proc  0.36    0.00  0.05  0.27  0.33  0.35   0.39   0.47   610 1.00

So in this case our estimate of nu (the degrees of freedom parameter) is much higher. In fact, it approximately matches the prior because the data are not informative about heavy tails. In this case it reverts to be effectively normal:

prior <- rexp(1e6, rate = 0.01)
prior <- prior[prior > 2]
hist(prior)
median(prior)
## [1] 71.28145
abline(v = median(prior), col = "red", lwd = 2)

This choice of prior is based on Fernandez C, Steel MFJ (1998) On Bayesian modeling of fat tails and skewness. J. Am. Stat. Assoc. 93(441):359371.

Since our models are fit in a Bayesian framework, one useful value to calculate might be the probability density below some threshold value for the degrees of freedom parameter. For example:

nu <- extract(m, pars = "nu")[[1]]
nu_hw <- extract(m_hw, pars = "nu")[[1]]

sum(nu < 10)/length(nu) # or mean(nu < 10)
## [1] 0.981875
sum(nu_hw < 10)/length(nu) 
## [1] 0.079375

Weve often used a value of 10 as a threshold since nu values much above 10 render distributions that are almost indistinguishable from the normal.

In the first case nu is less than 10 with 0.981875 probability. In the second case, there is only about a 0.079375 probability of nu < 10. Remember that even with the prior, there is some probability that nu < 10.

mean(prior < 10)
## [1] 0.07701475

An alternative prior, that we have used in our more recent work is gamma(shape = 2, rate = 0.1) as recommended in Juarez, M. A. and M. F. J. Steel. 2010. Model-based clustering of non-Gaussian panel data based on skew-t distributions. J. Bus. Econ. Stat., 28:5266.

Lets try a state-space version:

m <- stan("R/stan/gompertz-ss.stan",
  data = list(N = nrow(d), y = log(d$index), nu_rate = 0.01, sigma_obs = 0.05),
  iter = 2000, control = list(max_treedepth = 15, adapt_delta = 0.9))

# m <- stan("R/stan/gompertz-ss-est.stan",
#    data = list(N = nrow(d), y = log(d$index), nu_rate = 0.01),
#    iter = 4000, control = list(max_treedepth = 15, adapt_delta = 0.95), chains = 8)
e <- extract(m)
pred <- data.frame(
  est = apply(e$pred, 2, median),
  l = apply(e$pred, 2, quantile, probs = 0.025),
  h = apply(e$pred, 2, quantile, probs = 0.975),
  year = d$year)
ggplot(pred, aes(year, est, ymin = l, ymax = h)) +
  geom_ribbon(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point(aes(y = log(d$index)))
